<mjml>
  <mj-head>
    <mj-style> h2,img,p { margin:0; } p {margin-bottom: 10px;}</mj-style>
    <!-- <mj-font name="Roboto" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Roboto" /> -->
    <mj-font
      name="Roboto+Serif"
      href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Roboto+Serif:ital,opsz,wght@0,8..144,100..900;1,8..144,100..900&display=swap"
    />
  </mj-head>
  <mj-body background-color="#f9f8f9">
    <mj-spacer height="15px"></mj-spacer>
    <!-- Logo Header -->
    <mj-section
      background-color="#eff1f4"
      css-class="border-line"
      padding="1px 0.5px 1px 1px"
      border-radius="5px"
    >
      <mj-column background-color="#fff" border-radius="5px" padding="0px">
        <mj-spacer height="16px" />
        <mj-image
          padding="10px 12px"
          css-class="light_img"
          width="150px"
          src="https://www.businesshistory.co/logo-gray.png"
          href="https://www.businesshistory.co"
          alt=""
        />
        <mj-divider
          border-width="1px"
          border-style="solid"
          border-color="lightgrey"
          padding="10px 10px"
        />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            Every successful company has a turning point—a risk that paid off, a
            product that redefined an industry, or a decision that changed
            everything. However, not every story is one of triumph; some of the
            most valuable lessons come from the failures and missteps that
            shaped the business landscape.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <!-- <mj-divider border-width="1px" border-style="solid" border-color="lightgrey" padding="0px 0px" /> -->
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>
    <mj-spacer height="10px"></mj-spacer>
    <mj-section
      background-color="#eff1f4"
      css-class="border-line"
      padding="1px 0.5px 1px 1px"
      border-radius="5px"
    >
      <mj-column background-color="#fff" border-radius="5px" padding="0px">
        <mj-text
          padding="16px 12px 0px 12px"
          font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;"
          color="white"
        >
          <h2
            style="
              color: #8c3321;
              text-align: left;
              border-bottom: 2px solid #8c3321;
              font-size: 26px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              padding-bottom: 8px;
            "
          >
            Three private families, public power, and lasting impact
          </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-spacer height="18px"></mj-spacer>
        <mj-text
          padding="10px 12px"
          font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;"
          color="#000000"
        >
          <h2
            style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            "
          >
            The invisible giant
          </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            Just after the American Civil War, William Wallace Cargill saw that
            America was hungry. He realized the future lay not just in growing
            grain, but in storing, and he understood that railroads would be the
            backbone of agriculture. Realizing this, Cargill set up a
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #8c3321;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-09-08-2025-1-1-grain-warehouse?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >grain warehouse</a
            >
            right next to the tracks, cutting down transportation expense and
            time drastically. His simple yet brilliant strategy gave Cargill a
            huge competitive edge just as the US Midwest became the world’s
            breadbasket.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image
          border-radius="10px"
          padding="10px 12px 14px 12px"
          width="600px"
          src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/cargill-salmonir-omega3-spectroscopy-tech.jpg"
          alt="Cargill’s SalmoNIR technology uses near-infrared spectroscopy to provide salmon farmers with real-time data on things like omega-3 fatty acids"
          href="https://www.businesshistory.co"
        />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #a9a7af">
            <i>
              Cargill’s SalmoNIR technology uses near-infrared spectroscopy to
              provide salmon farmers with real-time data on things like omega-3
              fatty acids. Credits: Cargill</i
            >
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            From there, he partnered with his brothers and built a network of
            grain elevators that made Cargill the indispensable middleman
            between farmers and markets. By controlling storage and logistics,
            they shaped and controlled the flow of global agriculture. The next
            generation expanded beyond grain into cotton, meat, and anything
            moving across borders that was profitable and always in demand.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; filter: blur(5px)">
            Cargill distributes a wide range of products, including corn syrup,
            meat, and cosmetics. While many competitors went public,
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #8c3321;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-09-08-2025-1-2-cargill-remained-private?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >Cargill remained private</a
            >. By the 1980s, they were the largest privately held company in
            America, and arguably still are. The company remains 89%
            family-owned with over 100 family members as shareholders.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>
    <mj-spacer height="15px"></mj-spacer>
  </mj-body>
</mjml>
